The Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) has indicated that it will maintain restricted access to its office facilities, including its  trading floors across the country, and continue remote trading and business activities. The decision was sequel to governments’ ongoing efforts to reduce the socioeconomic impact of the COVID-19 pandemic by   gradually easing of the lockdown in the Federal Capital Territory, Lagos and Ogun States. The latest order entails a limit on all non-essential interstate travel, opening of businesses, markets and malls within designated hours, and a nationwide curfew between 8:00 p.m. and 6:00 a.m., except essential services. The Exchange noted that while it will continue to support the Government’s directives and efforts in the fight against COVID-19, it will prioritize the health and safety of its stakeholders, and will keep monitoring the evolving impact of this pandemic and make decisions in the best interest of our employees and stakeholders at large. Dear valued readers, subscribe to the Daily Trust e-paper to continue enjoying our diet of authoritative news. Kindly subscribe here According to the Exchange: “Our employees will keep on working from home except for essential staff who will continue to work out of the office as they have been doing since we commenced remote trading in order to ensure that our operations run smoothly and provide support. “We expect that you will continue to utilize all of our digital platforms at your disposal to trade remotely and engage with us. Further updates on our business continuity plans will be shared with our stakeholders in due course.”  NSE to sustain trading operations remotely - Onyema NSE lists N28. 9bn bond amidst economic slowdown Access Bank denies plan to sack 75% workforce, close branches